I max out the fuel, confirm the purchase, and leave the Exchange menu. The screen does the grey transition, but then I'm back at the planet menu, my money is gone from the purchase, AND SO IS THE FUEL. Like, am I being robbed, because if this is a "feature", getting ripped off with no warnings or pop-ups, I'll be seeking a refund. The game is WAAAAAYYYYY too damn cool to be locked out like this less than an hour in. The graphics are stellar, the text is clean and without typos, and the game runs like a top!

Long term update: I got the hankering to play this again, on my N5X, and the UI adjusts appropriately, making it usable on the smaller display of my phone, much less a tablet, even in portrait mode. The main status display on the map is small, but quite usable, unlike in the past. Now if Frontiers would just come out on Android...
replyContent: The game uses your configuration for fonts on device. If your OS fonts are too small, consider increasing the size. If you need any support, call or email me.  cory.trese@gmail.com

replyContent: If anything like a "pop-up ad" or a "virus" was placed on your phone, it was not by this game (Star Traders RPG Elite.) This game lacks INTERNET or PHONE_STATE permission and couldn't cause a pop-up on your phone even if it wanted to. I am sorry you are having problems with your Android device, but I think you have the wrong idea about ST RPG.

5 star fun, guarenteed!!  Star Traders Elite is the finest RPG in it's class. Highly intuitive touch controls hide a complex, but easy to understand economic gamesystem based around space trading. With a well developed background of Dune-like political intrigue among great houses and wealthy syndicates, the real story is told through the player's own choices...should i be a Star trader or a space pirate, a militarised assassin for hire or a stealthy smuggler? The choice is yours. Completing contracts earns you kudos among said factions, and with frequent trade you'll rise in that faction's military, giving access to new ships and weapons. With dozens of planets to visit and explore, unlimited ships to encounter, fight, raid, steal, upgrade or sell in your quest to captain the ultimate ship. With a well implimented learning curve, this is a fabulous RPG for newcomers and veterans alike. Advert free and permission free, Star Traders Elite is made by a top developer that constantly updates and genuinely cares, delivering top class entertainment that can be consumed in just 5 minutes, or over the course 5 hours. Star Traders Elite is a dream to play and without doubt the best in genre on google play. Highly recommended!!

These guys are two brothers who are translating childhood homegrown pen-and-paper RPG games into modern mobile games, and trying to earn a living doing it. Yes it's basic in looks but becomes in-depth at its core. Every decision you make depends on the next move. If you like this sort of game, start with the free version, learn, then pay the few dollars to get the paid version. It's worth it.

replyContent: Feel free to e-mail me at cory@tresebrothers.com about how to deal with the Xeno. They scale to difficulty level and do NOT appear on the lower difficulty levels. content: Fun and and casual, yet it has a fairly deep and complex strategy structure to it. Good replay-ability with the different levels and styles of play.   However, the large map on my LG G4 brings the flagship phone from half a year ago to a screeching halt. If the app doesn't crash, it takes 2-3 minutes to complete. This makes plotting courses a major pain.   Why still give it 4 stars? Because on my 5 year old Acer A500 tablet, this thing plays like a streamlined beast. It's the best performing application I've run on there in years. It's slick, immediately responsive and there isn't any buggy-ness with the rendering. I'm thinking this likely has to do with the pixel count and how much is trying to be drawn, the old tablet is only 1280x800 vs 2560x1440

content: You need to take the time to understand the game, but once you do, you have a superb game with many ways of playing and masses of replay value. These guys are great, they clearly love what they do and love their customers. I cannot recommend their games highly enough!!!!

Really liked the offline version went elite did not know that it was for online only I thought it upgraded the offline version as well but it doesn't very disappointed but other than that I like the game
replyContent: asa - sorry for the confusion.  ST Elite does not require online.  However, when you get a new update, you should open the game so that it can download app data from Google Play. Once that one-time download is complete, you don't need to be online again.

Thank you for creating a game with smooth game play as well as consistent graphics, sounds, story line, action, and free roam concepts. It's an unending journey that I hope continues in newer aspects. Genius!

The main problem is the lack of a plot, so if you don't devise your own plot, story, or goal, then this game can get old. I recommend this game. My tip is to pick a goal and fight for it. However I dislike in-game purchases, when you buy a game, you should get the whole game. Greedy Developer's are ruining the gaming industry.

content: This game has couple of unique attributes which lift it far above pretty much any 3x simulator out here: very well made dynamic economy, more or less endless pallete of ships, meaningful encounters, huge space with awesome lore, option of permanent death (I love this feature) and, above all, constant updates of the developers. As you move up in difficulty you must play more aspects of the game -- Conflicts, Rumors, Reputation, Caches, Politics, etc. There are a lot of great guides online, and you can also e-mail me at cory.trese@gmail.com for help!

replyContent: Sean -- my understanding of Google's Play Service is that you should only need to be connected to Google, via WiFi or 3G, to download and activate the updated version. After that, you should have no problem playing without any connection. If you are having device issues, please e-mail me at cory.trese@gmail.com

This game was a lot of fun at first but gets repetitive real fast.  I got the inquisition cruiser after earing a million creds or so, upgraded it, and aimlessly leveled to around 70.  What this game lacks is a plot, an ending.  Even leveling seems counter productive.  On the harder settings, the only way you get any challenge, your enemies level as a percentage of your level.  So the more you level, the greater the disparity and the greater distance between you and your enemys level.  You can have the nastiest upgraded capital ship and a small enemy fighter with a captain who has several levels on you will dodge your every shot and strike a manueverable vessel, and even board your ship with a 10th of your crew and in some cases just the captain himself can run through your ship unstoppably killing every last man! An insane game dynamic.  I've gone 1000 rounds on my level 69 crack shot captain missing every single shot, and that's not even against an alien, which of whom become monsterously impossible even with anti alienware and officers.  My solution? I started over and stayed level 8.  Fix your check system, get a plot, and this game would be gold.

replyContent: Thomas - the issue you are describing is caused by an Android option called "Don't Keep Activities" which is found in Settings > Developer Settings. This option runs down your battery and causes ST RPG (and most games) to glitch / crash. Turning it off will improve your Android experience. E-mail cory.trese@gmail.com for tech support

content: It reaffirmed my original irritations with this game. I got so laughably overpowered in Normal mode that I figured I'd go up to Hardened and try to unlock some of the rewards. Yea. Right. In Hardened and up you basically spend your first few hundred turns cowering with your tail tucked from pirates that enjoy an absurd numerical supremacy. They can move so quickly it's impossible to outrun them and they enjoy the use of ships that have many times the guns, armor and crew of any starting ship, so you basically have no choice but to constantly surrender your hard-won goods over and over. This is fine if you have the patience to "role play" a useless coward for hundreds of turns, but, personally, it's not for me, nor are "in app purchases" after the fact to unlock parts of the game I already bought.  I stand by my original conclusion. It's fun for a little bit, but it wears very thin very quickly with the dice roll mechanics and wildly uneven encounters and politics shifts.
replyContent: Thanks for playing -- with a little practice and some strategy you can easily last 50,000 turns. Details on the seemingly schizophrenic are plentiful in the game's manual (click the Help button) which should help you get a handle on Faction Reputation and Shalun Law. The fastest way to master the game is to practice on the lowest difficulty levels.

replyContent:
Paul -- very sorry to hear about the device issues. You need to turn off the option "Don't Keep Activities" in your Android OS and that will improve your battery life, system performance and fix all these issues with Star Traders and other games on your device.

Look under settings, once you uncheck it, things will be normal. Thanks for playing!

replyContent: The issues you are describing are caused by a setting on the device called "Don't Keep Activities" -- it will make apps malfunction (not to mention running your battery down.) When the phone is configured to destroy state, ST cannot save and transactions are lost. Sorry for the trouble. E-mail cory.trese@gmail.com if you are still stuck

replyContent: If it helps -- you can pick up on Shortages in the Spice Hall and see the spread between buy and sell in 'Resource Reports' which open when you tap the picture of the Resource in Cargo or Trade screens. For example, you can buy and sell Metals and Spice between Mining and Trade Economies for huge profits. Hope that helps...

replyContent: The key to trading is looking at the 'Economy Type' of the planets and using the 'Resource Report' which opens when you tap any resource icon in Cargo or Trade screens. There you can see all rumors, nearby prices for buying and selling. A clever merchant can buy low and sell high =)

Hey I own elite pirates, stars, and knights, I'm always a merchant type and their is a re occuring issue. Every update the planets towns, areas shop price info keeps on disappearing, why? This really screws with my trading so can this be fixed? BTW all games are amazing. Thanks
replyContent: The issue you are reporting, with trades not being saved -- that is caused by a setting on the device called "Don't Save Activities" which causes your battery to be drained and Star Traders trade data to be lost. If you need help fixing the tablet/phone please e-mail me at cory.trese@gmail.com and I will help you.

Best 3 bucks you can spend on Google play. They keep updating, and it already offers complex depth for those willing to rise up to the challenge.  You are the captain of a space ship, and the game let's you choose your play style for success. Are you trigger happy? Then there are several classes for you. Maybe you are a treky; that's fine too. You can get rich by killing, exploring, trading, doing missions, following rumors, and to some degree even by being a diplomat.  Your success is aided by character development strategy, your tactical choices, the officers you hire, and even the cargo you carry.

replyContent: That is very strange -- Star Traders RPG Elite does not have any permissions to look at your SD Card, so it actually cannot detect or request any information about it. Perhaps the error on the Nexus 7 is coming from the latest Google Play updates? I would love to try to help if you would like to e-mail me at cory.trese@gmail.com we can troubleshoot

Star Traders is a cracking little ol' skool space trading RPG, with all the depth and complexity you'd expect from a game with such a long spiritual heritage - but that's happy on the lower difficulty levels to let you zip about the Galaxy, safely poking things with sticks to figure out how they work.  Once you've figured out that it isn't all GO HERE. KILL THIS. or GO THERE. FETCH THAT, you can jump up to the higher difficulties and unlock new ships, upgrades, achievements and so on to reward your increasing mastery of Exploration, Combat, Leadership, Diplomacy & Trading.  5 stars, no filler.

Hands down the best game you can buy for Android. Why? It's massively addicting, complex and engaging, well supported both for bug fixes and new game features (so there's often something new to discover or achieve), always automatically saves your current game and lets you have numerous active characters running, doesn't hog your battery, and it costs $3. There's a big online support forum where users can report bugs, suggest new features, and even put up fan fiction based on their favorite captains. The game features interplanetary smuggling and trade, ship-to-ship combat, hundreds (if not thousands) of different ships, and management of ship and crew that can turn deadly if you aren't careful. Cannot beat the Trese Brothers on this one!

It is very easy to have 10 or 15 hours worth of gameplay snuff it over the course of a 20 second fight. Sure, there are ways to keep him alive but that involves a real compromise of game play... Ok, no elite style dog fights with other ships as it's a turn based combat system but this is a lightweight and easy game on a phone so that's understandable. Decide if you want to trade, bounty hunt, smuggle or be a pirate amongst other things.   Updated seemingly every few days by the Trese brothers and more ships and bug fixes (not that there's many bugs!) than you can shake a stick at.   The only downside that I can see, and it's a personal opinion, is that there is no coherent plot or quests other than the contracts you can do or the decision to rank up in the militaries or your captain's rank as this can seem to get a bit repetitive.....   This is the only game I have ever gone back to time and time again and well deserved of my 5 stars and the current average score of 4.8. Well done guys, keep it up!

The documentation could be a bit better as I went through some trial and error figuring out a few features & some of the game mechanics are still a mystery. Should run fine on just about anything, this style of game isn't about high-end gfx - it's a rich, complex environment for you to explore. Devs keep adding bonus material. If you're a fan of sci-fi and strategy games this is the title you've been looking for.

replyContent: You have accidentally turned on some of the 'Developer Options' in Android 4.x, which causes your applications (including Star Traders) to malfunction. To to "Settings > Developer Options" and turn off all the settings, especially "Don't keep activities" which is probably the issue here. Thanks for posting, glad we could help!

Where do I repair or refit armor? Where can you ream torpedoes?   Thanks for the reply.  Why does it consume water if I'm about to go to urban (to go to exchange) and new contacts (ships) keep popping up. It would be nice if you can see your status with the one hailing you.
replyContent: You can repair and rearm the combat components of your ship in a 'Military Base' which is located inside the 'Star Dock' on friendly and independent worlds. You can buy Guns, Torpedoes and Armor in the Military Base. Thanks for playing and e-mail if you have any issues.

I've said it before and have to say it again; the Trese Brothers have put together a truly brilliant title. 'Star Traders' is a roguelike strategy RPG that pulls no punches and has an incredibly satisfying difficulty curve that makes you hungry for more. Game mechanics are diverse and allow for critical thinking in heightening your chances of survival in the quadrant, while constantly shifting faction politics keep you on your toes. No permissions. Very regular updates. Feedback listened to. --- ★★★★★!

I ran across ST: RPG after finding Pirates and Traders.  This is a real gem: deep gameplay, a challenging learning curve across difficulty levels, plenty of variety in factions and ships, and useful unlocks for clever play.  I'm reminded of old turn-based games like Trade Wars 2002, and the setting is reminiscent of Traveler and Fading Suns pen-and-paper games.  The developers are more responsive than any I've seen, and devoted to avoiding annoying ad-based distractions.  The game is a masterpiece, yet still improving.  I only wish it was on the PC: its well-worth the burger-sized cost for the Elite version, which rewards you with more ship upgrades and other options.

Starting with the negatives... while it suffers from a clunky UI (almost everything is button driven), a daunting learning curve (many actions are extremely punishing and unforgiving of simple errors), a protracted lack of convenience features (no auto-purchase for fuel/supplies, no number entry to choose a specific cargo amount), some inconsistencies in the interface (press button here, select from list here), gameplay that sometimes feels like Microsoft Excel (number crunching), a lack of critical information at times where it is necessary (e.g., fuel consumed during landing, amount of fuel remaining after planetary exploration, etc.), and enforced unlockables, this game is both enjoyable and fun.  Its immersive, well-thought-out background is not very evident in actual gameplay, which is simultaneously a great accomplishment and a crying shame: those who want the back story can read the walls of text while those who just want to press buttons and make things asplode can ignore them. Don't be one of the asploders, though: the game is actually quite deep if you are willing to overlook its problems.  Don't bother with the Free version. The regular purchase is worth the pennies.

(played for 12 hours)  It would be great to see a mobile version of the classic space trading game Elite, but, unfortunately, ST isn't it.  There seems to be a decent game hiding under the covers.  Unfortunately, the user interface is so poorly designed that it actively fights against the player when it comes to understanding what's going on and carrying out your decisions.  The problem with this game is not that it is old-fashioned - there is nothing wrong with making a game that doesn't depend on fancy graphics.  But when one makes a game that is primarily text and option screens, it is mandatory to really think through how you organize the information & choices you're presenting to the user.  Information is presented to the user as large blocks of fill-in-the-blank text, when all you care about are two or three words.  This is OK if you only see this block of text occasionally, but, you're expected to read this identical blocks a dozen times in a minute of play.  The game isn't much about trading or space exploration - it's primarily about playing a balancing act between factions that get annoyed at you for a variety of reasons.  If that's your kind of thing, go for it.
